  </div>
    <p class="text">
      The implications of the image-making capabilites of new AI models is hotly debated. Through this and other experiments, I’ve challenged myself to explore potential use cases for AI that are unexpected and that challenge the seemingly dominant view that these new tools are simply copyright infringement machines. 
    </p>
    <p class="text">
      AI outputs are often measured by their ability to eliminate anomilies or inconsistencies - glitches - in their output images. In the case of making a camo pattern, these unwanted abstractions become functional. The glitches and repititions are exactly what’s needed to make a pattern that can serve its purpose as you move through different parts of an environment. 
    </p>
    <p class="text">
      The method involves using a dataset to provide supplemental training to an already generally capable base model (in this case a Stable Diffusion model tuned for forest patterns). This flexibilty to “learn” the features of an arbitrary dataset is what allows the outputs to be local and seasonal. 
    </p>
    <p class="text">
      With this exploration I hope to offer an alternate view on the use of AI for image-making - that this is a tool affording highly personalized designs that weren’t previously possible. In the larger narrative of this thesis project, I also hope to suggest that personal tools like this could facilitate a return to more local, seasonal ways of living. This camo is intended to be used for hunting and fishing, activities which demand a deep understanding of an environment, and which at their best represent a non-naive, hands-on stewardship of our natural environment. 
    </p>
  </section>

